# Charterwell — environment template
# Copy to `.env` and fill in values: cp .env.example .env

# --- Runtime ---
# NODE_ENV=development
# PYTHON_ENV=development

# --- LLMs (pick what you use) ---
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=
# OPENAI_API_KEY=

# --- Azure (Document Intelligence, OpenAI on Azure, etc.) ---
# AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT=
# AZURE_OPENAI_API_KEY=
# AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT=
# AZURE_DOCUMENT_INTELLIGENCE_ENDPOINT=
# AZURE_DOCUMENT_INTELLIGENCE_KEY=

# --- Search / RAG ---
# ELASTICSEARCH_URL=
# ELASTICSEARCH_API_KEY=

# --- Data stores ---
# DATABASE_URL=

# --- Cloudflare (agents / automation on your zone) ---
# Create an API Token: https://dash.cloudflare.com/profile/api-tokens
# Use least privilege: e.g. Zone → DNS Edit, Zone → SSL and Certificates Edit, etc.
# CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN=
# Account ID: dash sidebar (right) when a domain is selected, or Workers overview URL
# CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID=
# Zone ID: domain overview → API section on the right (per-domain)
# CLOUDFLARE_ZONE_ID=
# Optional: apex domain the agent should treat as canonical (no secrets)
# CLOUDFLARE_DOMAIN=charterwell.io

# --- GitHub Actions (Pages Direct Upload) ---
# Workflow uses GitHub **Environment** `production` by default (Settings → Environments).
# Put there (as environment secrets): CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN, CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID.
# If your environment has another name, add a repo **variable** CLOUDFLARE_ENVIRONMENT with that name.
# (Repo/org Actions secrets also work if you remove `environment:` from the workflow.)
#
# Cloudflare Pages (connected Git): Build output directory = out.
# **Deploy command: leave empty** so Pages uploads `out` itself (simplest; avoids API token issues).
# Optional: `npm run cf:pages:deploy` only if token is Account → Cloudflare Pages → Edit on the
# **same** account as the Pages project (else Wrangler auth error 10000).
# Non-production: empty or same as production — not `wrangler versions upload`.
# Never `npx wrangler deploy` for this static site.
# CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN — Pages Edit (same as above)
# CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID — Cloudflare account ID (do not put account_id in wrangler.toml for Pages)
